04066nam a22006615i 9781503605718DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202018cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2018296071  a97815036057187 a10.1515/97815036057182doi  a(DE-B1597)563875  a(OCoLC)1198931626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aKBP144b.A36 2018 4aKBP144 7aREL0370202bisacsh04a340.5/92231 aAhmed, Rumee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSharia Compliant :bA User's Guide to Hacking Islamic Law /cRumee Ahmed. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEncountering Traditions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Letter to My Muslim Readers -- tCHAPTER 1. What Is Sharia? What Is Islamic Law? What Is Hacking? -- tCHAPTER 2. Why Does Islamic Law Get Hacked? -- tCHAPTER 3. Who Hacks Islamic Law? -- tCHAPTER 4. How Does Islamic Law Get Patched? -- tCHAPTER 5. How Does Islamic Law Get Hacked? -- tCHAPTER 6. When Does Islamic Law Get Hacked? -- tCHAPTER 7. Where Does Islamic Law Get Hacked? -- tAfterword -- tAfterword -- tNotes 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over a thousand years, Muslim scholars worked to ensure that Islamic law was always fresh and vibrant, that it responded to the needs of an evolving Muslim community and served as a moral and spiritual compass. They did this by "hacking" Islamic law in accordance with changing times and contexts, diving into the interconnected Islamic legal tradition to recalibrate what was outdated, making some laws work better and more efficiently while leaving others undisturbed. These hacking skills made Islamic law both flexible and relevant so that it could meet the needs of a community with changing values while remaining true to its ancient roots. Today, the hacking process has stalled in the face of unprecedented structural challenges, and Islamic law has stagnated. This book is designed to revitalize the hacking tradition by getting readers involved in the process. It walks them through the ins and outs of Islamic legal change, vividly describing how Muslim scholars have met new and evolving challenges on topics as diverse as abolition, democracy, finance, gender, human rights, sexuality, and more. And it provides step-by-step instructions for readers to hack laws for themselves, so that through their engagement and creativity, they can help Islamic law regain its intrinsic vitality and resume its role as a forward-looking source for good in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aIslamic law. 0aLawzIslamic countries. 4aIslam. 4aIslamic. 4aMuslim. 4aSharia. 4afiqh. 4alaw. 4alegal. 4areform. 4areligion. 4ashariah. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360571840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605718423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605718.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles